  <div class="friendReviews elementListBrown" >
    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_3508244789" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3508244789" />
    <a title="Lucy" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/74034800-lucy"><img alt="Lucy" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1518091381p2/74034800.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3508244789?book_show_action=true">Aug 30, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Lucy" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Lucy" href="/user/show/74034800-lucy">Lucy</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780755384754" href="/book/show/17270883-shadow-of-night">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3508244789" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer12550540730815228314">2.5-3***<br/><br/><i>”You tell me that magic is just desire made real. Maybe spells are nothing more than words that you believe with all your heart.”</i><br/><br/>In this book Dianna and Matthew have timewalked to the year of 1590 in Oxford, England. Here they must search for the complete Ashmole 782. However, time walking has effects, and Dianna finds her magic playing up. <br/>Through this book we are able to see Dianna and Matthew’s search for Ashmole 782, the effects of the different time on their relationship, and Dianna</span>
  <span id="freeText12550540730815228314" style="display:none">2.5-3***<br /><br /><i>”You tell me that magic is just desire made real. Maybe spells are nothing more than words that you believe with all your heart.”</i><br /><br />In this book Dianna and Matthew have timewalked to the year of 1590 in Oxford, England. Here they must search for the complete Ashmole 782. However, time walking has effects, and Dianna finds her magic playing up. <br />Through this book we are able to see Dianna and Matthew’s search for Ashmole 782, the effects of the different time on their relationship, and Dianna taking control of some of her magic. <br /><br />Overall I found this book so unnecessarily long. So much of this was description of certain places during 1590, however, it’ll describe one thing to minute detail and move onto something else in minute detail, I just found myself getting so bored. I found the plot to this was also slow moving and some of the things that Matthew was involved with (so people he knew or jobs he had to do) just had me rolling my eyes. I also find that sometimes this book would mention highly intellectual or cultured topics and for someone like me, this could fly over my head or I just didn’t care. <br /><br />This definitely wasn’t action based or even magic based (which I really really wanted!). Most of the plot was just Matthew and Diana navigating their relationship... which just appeared so bleak on paper. I found their relationship and characters in this so much more one-dimensional and I got rather bored and annoyed at them. <br /><br />My favourite parts of this book were in the last 150 pages when we FINALLY get to see some things about Ashmole and see more magic and other witches. I really wish that the witches mentioned in this book were explored a lot more as their powers sounded so interesting and I was sad that this book had hardly any magic in it. This book does, however, include some questions that I do want answered.<br /><br />I can’t tell if this book just had “middle-book” syndrome and so I’m really questioning whether to carry on and finish the trilogy. While I didn’t hate this book it was super slow moving.</span>
  <a data-text-id="12550540730815228314" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

